\subsection*{Species traits}
Using the hazard function form with highest predictive skill (i.e. $(\alpha e^{-\beta X_{i}} + \gamma)\delta_t$; Fig.~\ref{fig1}b right), we examined how effects of a species' maximum dbh ($\psi$), light demand ($\upsilon$) and wood density ($\rho$) placed on $\alpha$, $\beta$ and $\gamma$ affected model predictive accuracy. In general we found that including trait effects on these parameters decreased logarithmic loss, and thus, increased predictive accuracy (Fig.~\ref{fig2}). Moreover, we found that incorporating the effect of all three traits on these parameters resulted in higher predictive capacity relative to models that only incorporated one or two of the traits. However, this increase in predictive accuracy was small relative to including species random effects on each parameter, which account for unexplained species differences, signifying that substantial inter-specific variation in mortality rates remains unexplained (Fig. \ref{fig2} Stage 6). See Tables S1 for trait coefficients and Table S2 or Figs. S3-S5 for species-level parameter estimates. 

