In order to examine how species traits -- maximum dbh, light demand and wood density -- affect tree mortality rates, we fitted a final model containing all three species traits and a species random effect (which captures inter-specific variation that unexplained by traits) on each of $\alpha$, $\beta$ and $\gamma$. We found that each trait influenced tree mortality in different ways (Fig. \ref{fig3}-\ref{fig4}). Specifically, we found that light demanding species were more susceptible to low growth rates (i.e. higher $\alpha$), had higher growth-independent hazards (i.e. higher $\gamma$) and exhibited shallower declines in growth-dependent hazards with increasing growth rates (i.e. lower $\beta$). By contrast, we found that wood density had significant impacts on $\alpha$ and $\gamma$, such that species with high wood density were less susceptible to low growth rates and had lower growth-independent hazards. Species' maximum dbh only had significant effects on $\gamma$, whereby species that can achieve larger dbh exhibited lower growth-independent hazards. Table S1 for trait effects on each parameter.
\subsection*{Parameter relative importance}

Using the final model, we then examine: 1) its ability distinguish between individuals that died and individuals that survived via AUROC; and 2) the amount of inter-specific variation the model explains (i.e. $r^2$) relative to the proportions of individual deaths observed per species between 1995 and 2010 (Table.~\ref{table:1}). We found that the full model had an AUCROC of \Sexpr{table1[[1,3]]}, indicating that the model had a fair ability to correctly discriminate observed deaths from survivals. Moreover, we found that the full model also explained \Sexpr{table1[[1,2]]*100}\% of the total variation observed among species.

